Here's my solution for this question. I'm not sure if there might be any edge cases that I'm not considering, but in my opinion this should do.

**My explanation:**
This explanation would be more intuitive to you if you've understood the 'Burst Balloons' solution.
So the main basic approach to this is similar to the 'Burst Balloons' question. But the main difference between 'Burst Balloons' and this question is the number of elements you delete. In case of 'Burst Balloons', you just remove one element. Whereas in this question you have to remove two at a time. 
So with that constraint in mind, our DP's subproblem would consist of removing any two pins in the range [left, right]. 
`dp[left][right]` = maximum answer you get by striking any two pins `i` and `j` (left <= i <= j <= right) in the end, considering that every other pin in the range [left, right] has been struck before. 
So, contrary to the 'Burst Balloons' solution where you needed one extra loop to find the element to delete, you need TWO loops in this one to find two elements to strike. These two loops are just simple loops to find two pairs of pins to strike in the range. But, you can't just leave it at that. There are more things to keep in mind than just finding any two elements. You need to find two elements such that the region to the left of the left pin (the range `[left, i-1]`) has to be even, the region in between to the two pins (the range `[i+1, j-1]`) has to be even, the region to the right of the right pin (the range `[j+1, right]`) has to be even. The reason why these regions are supposed to be even is because we're considering these regions to be struck and completely removed by the time we remove the `i`th and `j`th pins. So these regions are independent of each other, and can only be completely removed by themselves if they're even in size, because you keep striking two pins at a time, and they can only be completely removed if they have even number of pins.
In my code, I've represented these regions as `leftSection`, `midSection`  and `rightSection` respectively.
`beforeLeft` and `afterRight` denotes the element just before the range, ie., `arr[left-1]`, and the element right after the range, ie., `arr[right+1]`.
So the `dp[left][right]` would just be the sum of the subproblems obtained from the three sections `leftSection`, `midSection`, `rightSection`, and the product of the four elements `arr[left-1]*arr[i]*arr[j]*arr[right+1]`

**Time Complexity:** `O(N^4)` - Which bugs me to think that there might be another way to solve this problem.

I hope you could understand my explanation. Feel free to reply to this comment if you have any queries and I'll be happy to reply.

**My code:**
```
const int mod = 1000000007

long long solution(vector<int> &arr)
{
    int n = arr.size();
    vector<vector<long long>> dp(n, vector<long long>(n, 0));
    for (int left = n - 1; left >= 0; left--)
    {
        for (int right = left + 1; right < n; right += 2)
        {
            // choosing two pins b/w left and right (both inclusive) to strike:
            for (int i = left; i <= right; i++)
            {
                // if the range [left, i-1] have odd number of elements then don't consider it
                if ((i - left) % 2 != 0)
                    continue;
                for (int j = i + 1; j <= right; j++)
                {
                    // if the range [j+1, right] have odd number of elements then don't consider it
                    if ((right - j) % 2 != 0)
                        continue;
                    // if the range [i+1, j-1] have odd number of elements then don't consider it
                    if ((j - i) % 2 == 0)
                        continue;
                    // strike the ith and jth pins:
                    long long leftSection = i > 0 ? dp[left][i - 1] : 0;
                    long long midSection = (i + 1 < n && j > 0) ? dp[i + 1][j - 1] : 0;
                    long long rightSection = j < right ? dp[j + 1][right] : 0;
                    long long beforeLeft = (left == 0) ? 1 : arr[left - 1];
                    long long afterRight = (right == (n - 1)) ? 1 : arr[right + 1];
                    long long sum = (leftSection + midSection + rightSection +
                                     ((arr[i] * arr[j] * beforeLeft * afterRight) % mod)) %
                                    mod;
                    dp[left][right] = max(dp[left][right], sum);
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return dp[0][n - 1];
}
```

We have even number of balls, we have to consider in pairs. {If we consider consecutive pairs then some of them will be left without pairs}.

               For eg:-   [ 1 , 2 , 3, 4 , 5 , 1 ]
               If we consider [3,4] as last balls to be burst then call will go to left side with array as [1 , 2 , 3 ]  => 
               Here 2 remained without a pair as 3 is already pairs with 4

               If we consider [3,4] as last balls to be burst then call will right go to [4 , 5 , 1 ]  => 
               Here 5 remained without a pair as 4 is already pairs with 3 and 1 is end.

               Pair with last 1's is not possible as they are just using for adjacency.

               Thats why we will only consider every pair starting from odd index and not ewith even index.

